[2] Comoros
Date: Sat 27 Mar 2010
Source: Sante-Plus.Org [in French, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://sante-plus.org/breve663.html>


The Minister of Health, Hodhoaer Inzouddine, announced on Thursday
[25 Mar 2010] in a press conference in Moroni that 6 dengue cases
have been discovered in the Comoros. According to Dr. Goda, dengue is
dangerous only in its hematologic [sic; hemorrhagic] form. Dengue is
a viral disease known in the Comoros since the epidemic of 1948.
Following an increase in fevers recently in the Comoros, Hodhoaer
Inzouddine has sent blood samples to the Institute Pasteur
[laboratories] in Antananarivo, Madagascar for analysis.

Examination results of the tests of 17 blood samples were provided by
the Minister of Health at a press briefing on 25 Mar [2010]. The
results for the 17 samples indicate "6 cases confirmed positive for
dengue and 9 negatives, plus the 2 in which the tests cannot yet say
what it is exactly," said Hodhoaer Inzouddine.

Health authorities are now moving to review the data in order to give
an initial assessment of the disease and whether the archipelago is
actually subject to a dengue epidemic or [infection by the]
chikungunya [virus].

The Ministry of Health asked the Comoros population to protect
themselves against mosquitoes that are responsible for transmission
of the disease [virus] through the use of [insecticide] impregnated
mosquito [bed] nets. Furthermore, the Ministry of Health invites
people with symptoms such as fever and fatigue to go immediately to
the health center closest to their homes. It is inadvisable to use
drugs based on aspirin because of the risk onset of the hemorrhagic
form of the disease.

[Byline: Sandrine Magmaen]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-FRA
<promed-fra@promedmail.org>

[This article did not specify the [dengue virus] serotypes
responsible for this epidemic. Dengue can be caused by 4 types of the
virus (1,2,3,4) and has been the cause of major epidemics. Population
growth, uncontrolled urbanization, natural disasters and
impoverishment are involved. The disease has a significant economic
impact for some countries. In all cases, a fast and accurate viral
diagnosis is useful to confirm etiology for both the management of
patients and for public health surveillance systems in order to
launch the alert and strengthen the capacity of the anti-vector
fight. No specific treatment or vaccines are available today, but
several multidisciplinary studies are underway. The only existing
measure is mosquito control in the areas of concern.

A map of the Comoros can be seen at
<http://www.africa.upenn.edu/CIA_Maps/Comoros_19867.gif> and a
HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of the Comoros at
<http://healthmap.org/r/01b5>. - Mod.SC]

