[6] Brazil (Praia Grande, SP)
Date: Tue 30 Mar 2010
Source: O Globo [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://oglobo.globo.com/cidades/sp/mat/2010/03/30/praia-grande-a-5-cidade-do-litoral-de-sp-confirmar-epidemia-de-dengue-916213646.asp>


Praia Grande is the 5th city of Baixada Santista to declare a dengue
epidemic [Baixada Santista is an official metropolitan area on the
coast of Sao Paulo state originally centered around the port city of
Santos. Its administrative center is Santos. - Mod.TY]. Now there are
379 confirmed cases of the disease in the city. Most of the patients
are between 20 and 59 years of age. Confirmation was given this
Wednesday [24 Mar 2010] by the Mayor, Roberto Francisco dos Santos.

Santos, Sao Vicente, Cubatao and Guaruja now have joined this
[epidemic] situation. The number of confirmed [dengue] cases in the
region is greater than 5000.

During a news conference, the mayor of Praia Grande announced some
actions to try to contain the disease. One is the suspension of all
surgical procedures in hospitals. The measure goes into effect from
this Wednesday [31 Mar 2010]. The city also reserved 20 beds in the
Irma Dulce Hospital for hospitalization of [dengue] patients.

Also, laboratory tests (serology) to detect the occurrence of the
disease are suspended. All patients who come to health units with the
basic symptoms of the disease, such as fever, nausea, headache and
generalized pain, will be treated as though they have dengue.

In Praia Grande, the problem has especially hit the neighborhoods of
Vila Tupy, Vila Caicara and Jardim Real. Many of these residences,
said the mayor, have swimming pools. "Quiet water becomes an
attraction for the vector mosquito. Because of this, they are making
contact with the Public Ministry. The 1st step is a conversation with
the Public Prosecutor and 2nd with the prefecture Judiciary
Department and with the city council to create a law to fine these
people. We are also preparing a considerable joint effort by Easter,
especially in neighborhoods that have vacation homes."

Before Praia Grande, last Thursday [25 Mar 2010] it was the turn of
the Municipality of San Vicente to officially recognize that the City
is facing a dengue epidemic. The latest data of Epidemiological
Surveillance indicate that the municipality had up to then 1844
confirmed cases of the disease. There were another 252 suspected
cases of the infection. Guaruja city was the 1st to officially
announce its 5th [dengue] epidemic since 1997. The announcement was
made on 12 Mar [2010], when the city then had 962 confirmed cases of
the disease. Santos was the 2nd city to confirm the scenario [of a
dengue outbreak]. With the results announced by the Instituto Adolfo
Lutz last Friday [26 Mar 2010], the city has surpassed the level
maintained for an outbreak situation: 163 confirmed cases per 100 000
population. As of last Friday, the municipality now had a total of
680 cases. On Wednesday afternoon [24 Mar 2010], Cubatao also
officially took on [the position] of an epidemic state. In just 4
days, the number of cases jumped from 162 to 189, according to the
figures announced by that municipality on Thursday [25 Mar 2010]. The
city awaits the confirmation of another 422 cases of the disease.
Bertioga had its 1st dengue death last Friday [26 Mar 2010]. With 147
confirmed cases and 65 blood tests awaiting results, the city is now
working at an epidemic rhythm, although technically, it is not at
that stage. If this [a dengue outbreak] is confirmed, it will be the
1st time in the history of the city. Since the beginning of the year
[2010], the disease has caused the deaths of 20 people in the Baixada
Santista. The deaths have been registered in Bertioga (1), Guaruja
(7), Santos (7) and Sao Vicente (5).

--
