[7] Brazil (national)
Date: Thu 1 Apr 2010
Source: Pernambuco.com [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.pernambuco.com/ultimas/nota.asp?materia=20100401132114&assunto=31&onde=Brasil>


The number of dengue cases registered in the country up to 6 Mar
[2010] exceeds by 95 237 the total verified for the same period of
last year [2009]. According to the Ministry of Health, notifications
increased from 131 872 in the 1st 9 weeks of 2009 to 227 109 in the
same period of 2010. Of this total, 86.5 percent of the occurrences
were verified in the same states that registered the greatest number
of [dengue] cases last year [2009]: Rondonia, Mato Grosso do Sul,
Acre, Mato Grosso, Goias, Minas Gerais and Sao Paulo, where this year
[2010] 184 574 cases were registered. But, according to the Ministry
[of Health] up to 6 Mar of this year [2010], there was a decrease of
23 percent in fatalities and 81.2 percent in severe cases in
comparison with the 1st 9 weeks of last year [2009]. According to
data published by the unit, more than 1/3rd (35.4 percent) of
[dengue] notifications this year are concentrated in 6
municipalities: Campo Grande, (19 417 cases), Goiania (28 445), Rio
Branco (10 368), Belo Horizonte (9143), Porto Velho (5656) and
Aparecida de Goiania (GO), with 5027.

At the beginning of 2009, Minas Gerais had a [dengue] incidence of 99
cases per 100 000 population, but this year [2010], the incidence
increased to 243.2. The Ministry of Health considers the incidence of
dengue in Sao Paulo low in relation to other states, because the
proportion recorded this year is 28.7 cases per 100 000 population,
although there have been increased reports in relation to last year [2009].

In the entire country, the cases of dengue with complications and DHF
sum to 394 in the 1st 9 weeks of 2010, compared to 2097 registered in
the same period of last year [2009]. The number of deaths dropped
from 85 in 2009 to 65 in 2010, in the 1st 9 weeks of each of these
years. Records of deaths and severe cases can suffer changes, the
ministry said, once the tests are subject to laboratory investigation.

The Ministry of Health attributed the increase in cases this year
[2010] to an increase in temperatures and of rain in the whole
country. Another factor noted was the increased circulation of dengue
virus serotype 1 (DEN-1), present with greater intensity in the
decade of the 90s, which returned to spread in some states at the end
of last year [2009]. Also circulating in the country are serotypes
DEN-2 and DEN-3 viruses. When a person contracts dengue from one of
these virus types, according to the Ministry of Health, he or she is
immune to just that one and could be newly infected by [dengue virus
of] another serotype. And when a patient is infected more than once
[with heterologous dengue viruses], the risk of developing more
serious infection is increased.

According to his office, the [Health] Minister, Jose Gomes, sent a
warning to governors of northeastern states and the mayors of the
capitals recommending intensified action to eliminate mosquito
breeding sites of _Aedes aegypti_. He urged state and local
executives to join with other sectors that can help control the disease.

--
